  "format": "Sean Fennessey, Amanda Dobbins, and Chris Ryan draft 2019 across six categories (Drama, Action Horror Thriller, Oscar Nominee, Blockbuster, Streamer, and Wildcard), from Parasite to Avengers: Endgame.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "2019, before the draft",
      "note": "the year, and the Oscars that followed it",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Frozen II",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Chris says he didn't care for it even before he was a father, calling it a weirdly ornate, action-heavy version of the original."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Lion King",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The photorealistic remake, name-checked as part of the year's Disney glut."
        },
        {
          "title": "Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Sean recalls seeing it next to Kevin Smith and shouting along."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "draft",
      "heading": "The 2019 Movie Draft",
      "draftOf": "2019 movies",
      "note": "the comedy category was cut this year for lack of contenders; a new Streamer category replaced it",
      "categories": [
        "Drama",
        "Action Horror Thriller",
        "Oscar Nominee",
        "Blockbuster",
        "Streamer",
        "Wildcard"
      ],
      "teams": [
        {
          "host": "Amanda Dobbins",
          "picks": [
            {
              "title": "Portrait of a Lady on Fire",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Drama",
              "note": "One of Amanda's favorite films of the year, which she had ranked 13th on her own year-end list despite a recent poll placing it among the 30 greatest films ever made."
            },
            {
              "title": "Triple Frontier",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Action Horror Thriller",
              "note": "The Netflix heist movie. Amanda says it exists as a greater work of art in her mind than it does in reality, but stands by picking it over letting it go to Streamer."
            },
            {
              "title": "Parasite",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Oscar Nominee",
              "note": "Amanda's first-overall pick and her best movie of the year. Bong Joon Ho's eventual Best Picture and Best Director winner."
            },
            {
              "title": "Little Women",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Blockbuster",
              "note": "Greta Gerwig's adaptation, one of Amanda's favorite films of the year. She singles out Florence Pugh's Amy monologue."
            },
            {
              "title": "Marriage Story",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Streamer",
              "note": "Noah Baumbach's divorce drama, which Amanda says wrecked both Sean and Chris, who grew up as children of divorce."
            },
            {
              "title": "American Factory",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Wildcard",
              "note": "The documentary about a Chinese-owned Ohio factory, directed by Steven Bognar and the late Julia Reichert. It won the Oscar for Best Documentary Feature."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "host": "Chris Ryan",
          "picks": [
            {
              "title": "The Souvenir",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Drama",
              "note": "Joanna Hogg's film with Tilda Swinton, which Chris calls beautiful and a real arrival for Hogg as a filmmaker."
            },
            {
              "title": "Midsommar",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Action Horror Thriller",
              "note": "Ari Aster's follow-up to Hereditary. Chris says it disturbed him more than Hereditary did, and notes it's one of the only horror movies shot almost entirely in daylight."
            },
            {
              "title": "Once Upon a Time in Hollywood",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Oscar Nominee",
              "note": "Chris says he always drafts a new Tarantino movie first. Sean recalls Chris's birthday dinner at Musso and Frank right after seeing it."
            },
            {
              "title": "Avengers: Endgame",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Blockbuster",
              "note": "Chris takes it despite heavy ribbing from Sean and Amanda, calling it a fun collective theater experience even as he concedes he could have prioritized it earlier in the draft."
            },
            {
              "title": "The Laundromat",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Streamer",
              "note": "Steven Soderbergh's Panama Papers film with Meryl Streep, Gary Oldman, and Antonio Banderas. Chris calls it a masterpiece that was underseen because of its episodic, talking-to-camera structure."
            },
            {
              "title": "21 Bridges",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Wildcard",
              "note": "Chris calls it the movie he may have watched most from that year, and Chadwick Boseman's performance his favorite of Boseman's career."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "host": "Sean Fennessey",
          "picks": [
            {
              "title": "Uncut Gems",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Drama",
              "note": "The Safdie brothers and Adam Sandler. Sean calls it the emotional inverse of The Irishman and says it makes him feel alive."
            },
            {
              "title": "Ford v Ferrari",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Action Horror Thriller",
              "note": "James Mangold's racing drama, which Sean saw as the surprise opening-night film at his first Telluride."
            },
            {
              "title": "The Irishman",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Oscar Nominee",
              "note": "Martin Scorsese's gangster epic, which Sean has watched four times and calls a capstone on Scorsese's gangster mythology."
            },
            {
              "title": "Knives Out",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Blockbuster",
              "note": "Rian Johnson's whodunit, whose sequel Glass Onion was releasing the same day as this episode. Sean calls it a franchise that doesn't feel bound by franchise bullshit."
            },
            {
              "title": "High Flying Bird",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Streamer",
              "note": "Steven Soderbergh's second film of the year, shot on an iPhone, about labor and player empowerment in pro sports."
            },
            {
              "title": "The Lighthouse",
              "year": 2019,
              "category": "Wildcard",
              "note": "Robert Eggers' black-and-white two-hander with Robert Pattinson and Willem Dafoe. Sean recalls moderating a Q&A where Dafoe seemed entirely unimpressed with him."
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
